{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618241"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:22:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:22:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16505"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16505"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65521"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9196"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16505"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50960"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8509"},{"type":"tags","id":"10319"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21817"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65521"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESensory nerve fibers are classified based on their diameter, conduction velocity, and the types of receptors they innervate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerve fiber types primarily innervates sensory receptors that detect muscle length and rate of stretch?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type Ia fibers","Type Ib fibers","Type II fibers","Type III fibers","Type IV fibers"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ia fibers\u003C/strong\u003E are large myelinated axons that innervate the primary endings of muscle spindles. These receptors are specialized to detect both the static length of muscle and the dynamic rate of stretch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other fiber types have different functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ib fibers\u003C/strong\u003E innervate Golgi tendon organs which detect muscle tension\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType II fibers\u003C/strong\u003E innervate muscle spindle secondary endings and various cutaneous mechanoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType III fibers\u003C/strong\u003E conduct signals from mechanoreceptors and cold thermoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType IV fibers\u003C/strong\u003E are unmyelinated and primarily conduct pain, temperature, and crude touch sensations\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType Ia fibers have the largest diameter and fastest conduction velocity of all sensory fibers, allowing rapid transmission of proprioceptive information to the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type Ia nerve fibers innervate muscle spindle primary endings that detect muscle length and rate of stretch","Type Ib nerve fibers innervate Golgi tendon organs that detect muscle tension","Type II nerve fibers innervate muscle spindle secondary endings and various cutaneous mechanoreceptors"],"references":["Ward RE, Boudreau RM, Caserotti P, Harris TB, Zivkovic S, Goodpaster BH, Satterfield S, Kritchevsky SB, Schwartz AV, Vinik AI, Cauley JA, Simonsick EM, Newman AB, Strotmeyer ES; Health, Aging and Body Composition Study. Sensory and motor peripheral nerve function and incident mobility disability. J Am Geriatr Soc. 2014 Dec;62(12):2273-9. doi: 10.1111/jgs.13152. Epub 2014 Dec 8. Erratum in: J Am Geriatr Soc. 2015 Mar;63(3):625. PMID: 25482096; PMCID: PMC4270855.","Wang Y, Pessin JE. Mechanisms for fiber-type specificity of skeletal muscle atrophy. Curr Opin Clin Nutr Metab Care. 2013 May;16(3):243-50. doi: 10.1097/MCO.0b013e328360272d. PMID: 23493017; PMCID: PMC4327989.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50960"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16505"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50960"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T15:10:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T23:26:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9196"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65521"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/